comment: Thanks. In bleak midwinter I needed a healing day

It seemed impossible but I tried to let myself be present and know that I can pick up worry and anxiety and struggle right where I left it. But I don't need those to do yoga. It showed me a bit about how I am not my demons. I am something separate, even if they hijack my life and my will, they are not me. Happy to be here, I do hope I am healing.

I understand that some people need reassurance and someone telling them “they can do it” but I don’t. I’m sorry if it sounds like I’m trashing you but I’m not I just don’t need all the extra, tell what to do and how long to do and what the next position is and let me focus on all the things I need to focus on. They’re physically good workouts but not enough quite time to focus on the mental part.

This one is going in my bookmarks bar. Something really clicked for me in this video. I think this is the first time I've ever entered a mediation as deeply as I did in the first part of this session. I lost myself to my breathing all while still somehow being present in and mindful of my body and I cannot tell you how much of a gift that is for me: Breathing and paying attention to my breath used to be incredibly panic-inducing for me so that I was able to do this is huge. And it was so healing. I started your videos a few months ago and I did breath in June and it was really difficult for me because of all the breathing (but nowhere near as bad as it has been, partially because of my place in my healing process and partially because of the way you handled it)...and while my relationship with my breath grew through that month, I never quite managed to experience what you spoke about with respect to your relationship to your breath. This isn't the first time in one of your videos where something has clicked in a particularly healing way-- usually, it happens when I don't really expect it to and I've cried, processed, and/or released something a few times--thank you for all of those moments but especially thank you for this one because it was more expected in this one and so I got to process it in this very cozy and nurturing place.

I have to share the craziest thing that has ever happened to me. 

When she said, "Blanket yourself in love.", my awareness faded for a moment. I actually saw my 8 year old self sitting in my childhood room. Lost, lonely, crying. I walked up to her and wrapped the blanket around her. I told her it was okay and where we are today. How strong she was. Adrienne's voice in the background. 8 year old me heard her for a moment, looking up and around, eyes scattered. We made eye contact, boom, I was back. Tears streaming. 

Thank you Adrienne. I literally blanketed myself in love today. I think I traveled time and changed the past in some way. Never in a million years would I have imagined that something like this would happen after joining a 30 day yoga challenge at home. 

I am so very thankful for you.

At first, I did not understand how this yoga class could lead me to healing as it said in the title, nor did I think I ever needed healing. I came to the class looking forward to the stretches because it felt really good to get my body moving at really slow and guided pace. As I gave myself time to be still during this class, I realized that was the kind of healing that I needed - to be still and to surrender, to give myself *permission* to do absolutely nothing. I was always the steady kind of person and I always thought that it was wrong that I am this way, not as fast paced as everyone else in the world. It is one thing to be relaxed and steady and still but it is a different and beautiful thing to be consciously allowing yourself to be so. 

At first, I thought I was only breathing in and out like she said not knowing that that was what it was like to blanket myself, breathe in and breathe out love. When you asked me to notice how I feel and notice any changes in my breath, there were tears in my eyes - tears of love and gratitude. It's funny and comforting reading the comments that other people experience it too. As I was still on my back against the earth I caught myself saying thank you for allowing myself this time with you.

I like what you said about surrender. "As we surrender to that which is bigger than us, there is a beautiful opportunity to recognize the surrender as actually a unity - an idea that we are part of that which is bigger than us." It truly is beautiful and I'm excited to explore more of it with myself through your guidance! Thank you Adrienne! <3

At the beginning of this journey I set the intention to be more aware of the choices I make, with some focus on how I make decisions when it comes to food and sustaining my body. Today I had chosen to keep this practice for later in the evening and do a more active practice during the day, but some part of me knew I was just going to skip day eight - I'm here to make conscious choices that are good for me, after all. Relaxing like this is not something my body deserves just yet. Need to lose some weight first. 

A sentiment I thought I had transcended, but something I need to keep bringing myself back to. It's so easy to lose your way sometimes.

As I'm writing this it's well past three in the morning, it's storming outside and the wind is literally howling, throwing itself at the house, has been all night, and earlier tonight some sort of restlessness crept up on me. I felt wide awake, in an almost jittery way. It's a feeling I'd normally numb with food, but the intention I have set actually works. Today I didn't feed myself things my body doesn't need, things my soul just craves for a lack of understanding what it does really need. But the amazing understanding, the choosing not to cave in to something habitual like that, doesn't mean the restlessness just goes away. 

Some sweet, soft voice in my head gently reminded me of the practice I had promised myself earlier today - a promise I very well knew had been empty. I was watching a series on my laptop, my love sleeping calmly in the room next to me. And without even second guessing it, I gave in. I finished the episode, prepped my yoga mat with all the blankets and pillows I was going to need to make this practice as comfortable and loving as possible. Then without any fussing I gave into it. 

I had my eyes closed for practically the entire session. I had noticed Adriene had let her hair down and did the same. Appreciating the way that felt. Feeling connected without the pinch of guilt or shame or whatever you'd like to call it, that, for me, normally comes with wanting to believe you're connected to someone who's just so far above you in so many ways. I felt like I was practicing with a dear friend today. I think I was a dear friend, my dear friend, today, too. And that feels incredibly nice.

Thank you, Adriene, and without a hint of cornyness, Namaste to everyone involved, everyone practicing and everyone on a journey - wherever you're headed (because I'm going somewhere too).

Wow! Just. Wow. Thank you dear Adriene. Thank you for the connection. Thank you for the healing. thank you for Home. I started home this January. I started late but that's okay. That is the freedom you nurture for us all. That it's okay. That we're okay. I think I started sometime in the second week of January and I may have made it to day 5 (not consecutively, I might add and that's okay. Do what feels good, right?). I loved that the 30 day practice was called Home. Home has always been a big theme for me and I even played for a time with branding a logo around my teaching practice using H'Om as the name of my traveling yoga studio. 

Now today, I find myself doing this practice, this day 8, feel great, don't hate, meditate practice. And the irony dawns on me. How back in January were we to know just how meaningful the Home series would be. And all this time we have been home, what has been happening? In many ways, a great healing is taking place. The broken places in our homes, our hearts, our world are being healed.There is much sadness and grief and anger and frustration and denial  and guilt and fear. But healing is taking place. 

Healing is taking place in me. Healing for the loss of my father 5 years ago. Healing for the loss of my mother just over one year ago. Healing for the broken places in me from the trauma of childhood abuse. Your words are always just what I need to hear at the time. I now have some new song lyrics stirring in my brain because this practice left me with "tears in my ears" as I lay in savasana. Tears are good for healing. You, dear Adriene, are a bright shining light! Namaste

Like many others I started this journey in the midst of the coronavirus outbreak. I am a high risk individual due to (apparently) severe asthma, and not only that but I suffer with anxiety and OCD anyway, so I'm constantly worrying that I've somehow contracted the virus even though I know it's incredibly unlikely for that to have happened to me since I have completed 2 of my 12 weeks isolation. I used to practice yoga and meditation fairly regularly but had stopped until about 2 weeks ago, when my home country, the UK, went into lockdown. At the time of writing, our UK Prime Minister is in an ICU with coronavirus, so on top of all the other chaos this virus is causing, we're all worried about him too. Since rediscovering the wonders of yoga, though, I feel calmer, even if it's only a little bit some days, in the midst of all this anxiety in these unprecedented and scary times. This healing practice today really helped me to get cosy, take time for myself and relax as best I can during these times. Whilst I'd be lying if I said my mind was completely still during this practice, what it did do is allow me to come back to myself and to practice being more aware of my breath and my feelings. Thank you Adriene (and Benji) for helping me on this journey to a better me. You are a blessing to this world ❤

I have started a few other 30 day practices in the past, but never got further than day 5 or 6. I never managed to find the stillness needed, always found excuses to skip a day until I just stopped all together. 
I started this practice about a week into self isolating after many months of feeling like I needed to do "something". And perhaps it is the idea that there is more time now, or perhaps it's because it's the start of spring and everything is feeling softer and newer, or perhaps it's that this global crisis, as horrible and daunting as it is, is giving me a feeling of connectedness, a belief that, for once, everyone in the world is doing the best they can to keep each other safe, but I have no issues now to show up every day. Because that's what it is I think, it's not whether or not I'm motivated, it's simply a desire to show up, every day, in many different ways, and one of them is on the mat.

I never knew that one can get mentally strong with yoga, that one can collect himself, become aware of who he is and fell in love with the treasure that is ourselves with yoga. I've gone through depression, a time where my thoughts were out of my control and were affecting my health. Constant dark thoughts and holding onto unhealthy memories caused stiff muscles and for weeks, I would get stuck in bed, unable to even move my arms. Everything would hurt. When I started this journey 'Home', I felt relaxed after each days practice, calm and motivated. I've done yoga before, about seven to eight times, for my stiff shoulders, and I cried once or twice after a good meditation. Tears would spill out of my eyes, disturbing my breath.


I cried again today. I've healed. I feel strong. I'm busy with life and happy. I've gone, from the constant overwhelmedness to sharp pain bringing panic attacks. From icy numbness to a lost feeling. I'm quite happy these days. I've grown stronger, but today, after doing this practice, I found a tear or two leak out of my eyes, and I felt hope deep inside. I healed again today, and I fell in love again. With myself. And you. Thank you so much for being utterly yourself, and for this journey home. My body, my mind, my heart, it all feels like 'Home' today. 



Love from Pakistan.

Dear Adriene, I found you about two weeks ago when I looked for a yoga stretch after my run. Straight away fell in love with your way of teaching, the fun, cheerfulness and the ease you invited me into your home. Now with everything that's happening in the world, I thought it a good idea to follow your 30 days of yoga. So I started last week, right when I heard that I will have to stay home for the foreseeable future, as my job is closed for now. I don't mind staying home, it makes me be creative and love my little space, the garden, my plants, and so on. But doing yoga with you has made staying home even better. HOME has found a place in my home. Day 6 was a tough one, at the start of my own cycle, lots of emotions, feelings, feeling like doing nothing all day, but I still made it to the mat. I wasn't perse satisfied but I did it, and it was fine. BUT then, the next day, day 7 I woke up with sore muscles and it felt SO good, I did that. So it took me a day to feel satisfied, but I was happy and proud that I made it to the mat on that day 6. Day 7 truly was super helpful. And now today, again a lot of emotions, hormones, you know the tea. It almost feels like your 30 days of yoga are perfectly synced with my life, my moods, my days. It's incredible really. This was, again, exactly what I needed today. To cover myself with love, hold myself and be in the moment. Thank you so so much. I'm very excited for the rest of the 30 days, and every single day that will come after that. Hope you're doing well and taking care of yourself. Thanks for creating this community, I feel like I've finally come home.

This year I promised myself I would do something to actively heal some of my pain in his honor. One of my daughters said, "Mom, you have to try Yoga with Adrienne."  Eight days ago, I started the 30-day practice and I'm so glad to have a kind voice and healing teacher to meet me every day.  Today, when we lay our hands out palms up for Shivas Ana, my dog Kai (who attends every class) put his paw in my hand. Healing in every way.  Then Adriene says "I love you" and I felt it.  Thank you.

Hi Adriene,
I've been practising yoga nearly every day for about two years now, using your tutorials on You Tube for an at home practice. I decided to take up yoga to try and heal chronic back pain, or at least become better at living with/ despite it and ignoring it. My brilliant and skilled chiros and osteos could not do enough in their sessions each week/ fortnight to rectify an injury arising many years before. Daily yoga works, for so many reasons.
 At over 55, your guided yoga practice, provided with so much heart, thought and goodwill has healed that injury, and increased my flexibility. It enables me to perform better on trapeze, which I started learning about 5-6 years ago, and gives me better posture too, no doubt. There is so much truth to your philosophy, and how we learn on the mat reflects how we learn and cope in every day life. THANK YOU. Namaste.

Healing shows itself in so many different ways. I was having a bit of an anxious morning before I came to the mat. As a result, I couldn't do the deep breathing in time with Adriene - I think I managed to do only one full cycle of breath. But instead of getting anxious that my breathing was so shallow, or panicking that I couldn't breathe deeply, or berating myself for not completing a "perfect" practice, I just let it be and allowed my body to "find what feels good", letting those judgemental thoughts pass through and away. And while that might seem small for some, for me that was everything. Namaste!

Until now it has been difficult to find the words, but I feel now is the time to thank you, dear Adriene. I found you almost 3 years ago, I found you when I needed you, when my life fell apart. You have helped me through divorce, through losing someone I love, through losing my home, and losing myself. Words cannot express how grateful I am for your presence in my life. You saved me, you helped me to save me. You have reminded me to be kind to myself, you have helped me to find calm and breathe through the most heartbreaking, anxious and stressful of times. You, sweet friend, and this community have made me feel as though I am not alone. It's been quite the journey, and it's not over yet, I am so grateful to have you by my side as I continue on this path. Until now I have dipped in and out of the practices, choosing what type of practice I needed at the time, this is my first 30 day yoga journey with you, I finally feel able to commit. I wish for you to know how much I value you Adriene, and what a difference you have made to my healing process. You are a blessing. I thank you from the bottom of my heart. Namaste, Amanda

I was dreading a practice like this so much. It scares me, being still and not being able to focus on anything but what's inside. Instead of finding peace, I feared it would bring up all the emotional chaos instead. But since a few months I've committed to this recovery journey. Trying to let go of my beliefs over myself, my body, my feelings and thoughts, I thought that maybe now would be a good moment to just try it. To just go into the practice without the expectation of it being perfect, of it being easy, of it being peaceful. I just wanted to see what would happen. And it was a bit difficult, but I'm proud that I tried, that I stuck through the entire practice, and didn't give in to the need to "move more" or the thoughts about being lazy. I did what I had to do ;) the practice of day 8. Without this journey I'd never have clicked on a practice like this, and now that it belongs to the journey, I felt more open to trying it anyway. A very long story to conclude that I'm a little proud of myself, and grateful for the safe space here where I can explore.

I don't often comment on youtube videos, but after doing those star stretches yesterday I had a dream 
last night about touching the stars and wrote a little poem about it:



I touched the stars in my dream last night

laughed in awe as I ran my fingers through their celestial bodies

floated in an ocean of inky blackness

watched as the universe slowly cartwheeled around me

and when I wanted to return to earth

I collapsed and crumbled and plummeted like a comet

I'd like to think my dreams were reminding me of where I came from

perhaps, for the briefest of moments

taking me home



I didn't even realize I was writing a poem about going home until I finished it. Life is such a bizarre, beautiful little thing isn't it.

Find what feels good yoga has been an incredible source of support as i do this. my healing has been done mostly on my own, because no one else can give me what i need to give myself. all of the self love talk is so helpful as i am trying to love on all the versions of myself that have suffered. it makes me feel like im not alone, like everyone else who is doing their own healing is here with me. im happy to say i dont feel like the world is just a dark place anymore.

My insecurities have been the cause of many of my most expensive mistakes, because I willingly gave my time and energy to those who discounted my own--two things I can never make more of. And there are days when I wake up and think about something that happened years ago, but I'm getting better at letting it flow through me. As Seneca mentioned: "We suffer more in imagination in reality." To keep thinking of something I suffered once is to suffer it over and over again. I've been applying this to my life, and I hope this helps someone else on their path to healing 🙏

This yoga practice was a miracle. I have been doing your videos on and off for about a year. This morning, I went upstairs to set up for yoga. Usually my husband (who has been dealing with cancer for 2 1/2 years) leaves the room and goes to his desk to work, but today he stayed. Perhaps it was because you mentioned a blanket and pillow and he was already in bed, but for the first time ever, he did the practice with me. I could hear him breathing along with me, him on the bed and me on the floor. Then he continued when we sat up and did the twisting stretch. Later as you guided the facial relaxation tears were streaming down my eyes, imagining him relaxed, feeling at one with the universe, letting go of thoughts of illness. After the practice I lay down over him and blanketed him with love. That we did this yoga practice together this morning was a miracle.

Today's practice came at the perfect time.  I took our daughter back to college after a wonderful holiday season together.  My heart was full of sadness and joy as I watched her had happily return to her new life at school.  I was also a bit apprehensive with the concept of healing and learning to love myself.  As a survivor of childhood abuse I learned to fear physical touch and became very uncomfortable with the concept of loving myself or letting others love me back.   I rarely, if ever, take the time to quietly lay still and connect with my soul and start the healing process.  Ugh that is so uncomfortable for me to even write.  But, today I did and feel all that better for it.  The self hug today was wonderful, and I didn't even squirm away from this like a teenage boy getting a loving hug from grandma.  Progress.

I love this slow meditative practice. Usually when there is a meditative practice where we are asked to get a blanket or a pillow, I'll grab a towel and do it. But today I went all out, I got a blanket and a cozy sweater and some tea and a soft pillow. I feel whole within myself and one with the universe. Breathing love in and out is such a powerful idea for me. To believe that the universe is made of nothing but love and to take it into myself and then to put it back into the universe, is truly a healing experience. I have been adding a meditation practice after each yoga session, I'll sit and meditate for 10-20 minutes. and today I took the invitation to stay wrapped up in my blanket lying on the floor breathing in love. I feel whole today. A good feeling. I'm very grateful for this practice.

During december i got a hold of my long lasting depression with medication and started to go out and socialize more. I learnt many need skills and even after new years i have been on a high drive, being more active in life than ever, filling every moment with things to do. I was so glad to start your challenge and with this practice i realized that mental health isn't only the ability to be productive or active, it's also having the skill to acknowledge when your mind and body needs rest. I fell asleep during this practice and I'm glad I did, because my body, mind and soul could take what they needed : rest, and love💓🌹🦋💕🌸💘💖🌱 thank you for beautiful experience😊🦋🌸🙏🏽 i will make sure to rewind and sleep more from now on! 😊

He came very sweetly and covered myself with a cover while I was already in bed, and I remembered thinking something like "another typical thing by x (my friend's name)". And after 2-3 years from this memory, I was invaded by appreciation for his kindness and his attention, which was already one of his characteristics but I never appreciated it while we were together as I should. Now he's in another country and I thought: " how many acts of love I didn't let feel in my heart, how I close my heart to one of the most beautiful things on this planet.... random kidness. This is the intention of the year for me. To open this heart, beacuse its has been closed for so so long, it is going to become too blind. Oh my God. Thank you, Adriene <3
